<section xml:id="sec-labpython-plotting" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Producing Line Plots</title>
    <p>
        Once data is accessible in Python, data analysis and visualization can be performed. As an example, let's assume that we've conducted an experiment on the circuit shown in <xref ref="fig-labpython-plotting-vdiv"/>. In this experiment, <m>V_\text{in}=5.0\text{V}</m>, <m>R_\text{fixed}=5\text{k}\Omega</m>, and we measured <m>V_\text{out}</m> as <m>R</m> was varied between <m>0-10\text{k}\Omega</m>. The code below produces a plot in which the data is represented as closed circles and the theoretical prediction is represented as a solid line.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-labpython-plotting-vdiv">
        <caption></caption>
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image>
            <xi:include parse="text" href="./figures/fig-labpython-plotting-vdiv.ptx" />
        </latex-image>
        </image>
    </figure>
    <sage language="python">
        <input>
            globals().clear() # Clear all variables from previous code runs

            import numpy as np
            import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

            plt.close('all') # Close all open figures

            # Data points
            R = np.array([1000, 2000, 3000, 4000, 5000, 6000, 7000, 8000, 9000, 10000]);
            V = np.array([0.815, 1.332, 1.880, 2.238, 2.614, 2.777, 2.881, 3.289, 2.974, 3.096]);

            # Theory curves
            Vin = 5.0 # Volts
            Rfixed = 5000 # Ohms
            Rth = np.arange(10000);
            Vth = Vin*Rth/(Rfixed+Rth);

            # Plotting routine
            plt.plot(R, V, 'o', label='Data');
            plt.plot(Rth, Vth, label='Theory');
            plt.xlim(0,10500);
            plt.ylim(0,3.5);
            plt.xlabel(r'Resistance ($\Omega$)')
            plt.ylabel(r'$V_\text{out}$ (Volts)')
            plt.legend();
            plt.show();
        </input>
        <output>    
        </output>
        </sage>
        
